<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>In 2020 I started the course "Deep Learning for Coders" from <a href="https://fast.ai">fast.ai</a>. As one of my projects, I had to train an image classifier (fine-tune a Resnet model with fastai's wrapper around PyTorch, specifically).</p>
<p>I wanted to use a dataset that no one had tried before, so I acquired the book cover images from the paper <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1610.09204">Judging a Book by its Cover (2017)</a>. Citing the paper here:</p>

<pre><code>@misc{iwana2017judging,
      title={Judging a Book By its Cover}, 
      author={Brian Kenji Iwana and Syed Tahseen Raza Rizvi and Sheraz Ahmed and Andreas Dengel and Seiichi Uchida},
      year={2017},
      eprint={1610.09204},
      archivePrefix={arXiv},
      primaryClass={cs.CV}
}</code></pre>
<p>The authors achieved 24.7% accuracy. As we'll see below, mine achieved 33.7% accuracy -- not amazing, but SOTA for the time. I called this book cover judger "Legiblate", for unknown reasons.</p>
<p>I later decided to upload Legiblate to Heroku as a Streamlit app. I had to retrain a smaller resnet34 model for that, as the resnet50 version wouldn't fit on a free dynamo. That model had 32.8% accuracy and you can find the <strong><a href="http://legiblate.herokuapp.com/">Legiblate app here</a></strong>. Note that if the site has not been accessed recently it will take a few seconds to load, as the free dynamo boots up.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Some unfortunately predictable results here: things like "The NLP Cookbook", which is a self-help book whose cover actively mimics a cookbook, or <em>Rabbit, Run</em> which is a novel but is represented here by some garish edition with only a basketball on the cover.</p>
<p><strong>Book design doesn't have a <em>direct</em> relation with genre, only a conventional one. The fact that this net can guess 1 out of 3 correctly is pretty amazing. Random guessing would get you 1 out of 30, an order of magnitude different.</strong></p>
